[[File:CanivalStar.mp3|thumb]]

Below is the account of a Russian wanderer who currently resides in a level long since lost in the M.E.G database. 

== Introduction ==
Hello friend! It appears you've come across the tale section and found that you wanted a place to stay safe from all those wretched, horrifying..."creatures". 

What if I told you such a place existed? Such a place where you can also relive your childhood as long as you want?

Well, friend, that's what i'm presenting to you right here, right now. 

My name is Maslov Voshevlec, and this is my story of my experience in this nostalgic childhood haven

== The Discovery ==
Like every fellow explorer in this...otherworldly hellhole, I was wandering through that "Storm Chaser" level, driving down a muddy road, minding my own business, letting the wind, the sound of the truck engine, the faint thunder, everything flood my senses. I had already been driving for a good 4 hours in an old truck. I had done some research of this level previously and was using that level to get to the hub for a shot of vodka. I've always wanted to go to levels where I can have access to The Hub. Yeah, I do love my alcohol.

I see the environment getting darker around me, and the clouds disappearing along the horizon. You know that this should never happen. I snap back to my senses, and I devote a massive amount of awareness to the environment. Nowhere in the level database has mentioned there being any daylight changes besides some crazy weather event. This I've ruled out due to the sudden lack of clouds. Ahead, the road soon turns into a barely visible trail of tire tracks and dead grass, with mud pooling in every tiny gap along the trail. Up ahead, I see neon lights. Beautiful blues, bright purples, vibrant greens, all seamlessly merging together light a beautiful light show. In the distance, odd looking rock formations and multistory buildings take shape, enveloped in that same neon hue.

Civilization?



Finally?


An End?


A way back home?


Or a trap?

== My Arrival ==
Going 90 kilometers an hour on that bumpy grass trail, I race towards that glorious mix of rock concert colors. Those rock formations becoming bigger, those buildings growing taller, and small, bright colored tents come into view. A million thoughts go through my mind. People, food security, easy access to water, safety, my brain is on an imaginary overdrive, unbale to process and sort through millions of thoughts, scenarios, etc. The goal was still the same in the end. It hasn't changed.



As I approach this...Carnival? Yeah, Carnival, I slow down the truck at an old, chain-link fence, with an open gate in the center, flanked on both sides by those same rock formations. Along those formations are a set of stage lights, each light emitting those same colors, slowly fading into various neon colors, and eventually cycles back into a bright purple before repeating. Beyond the gate is a long, brick sidewalk. On either side of the sidewalk are rows upon rows of carnival tents, rides, and those occasional giant buildings and rock formations. Lampposts and speakers dot the corners of intersections or hang off some of the rocks if there are sidewalks alongside those said formations. These speakers are incredibly bulky. Say, do they know about compact products?

I take a super motivated half-stroll, half-run through the stone streets of this mega-carnival, eyes widened like dinner plates at each tent. Standard ring tosses, Target practice with various magazine-fed weapons, outdoor arcade machines, full-sized basketball courts, soccer & and football fields, slushie machines, food stands, and a slew of other things you would find in such a location. Oddly, there was no actual humans. The only living thing here were these brightly colored fire people. I've read about them before. These fiery people are called Glowfolk. They're super friendly and playful, and a little crazy in the head.

Soon, one of these guys grabs me on the shoulder.

== The First Game ==
I whip around to see one of those Firey gentlemen behind me, and points to a nearby carnival game. Ring toss with a ton of colored duckies enclosed in a dark purple tent. 2 racks are situated on the front 2 support beams of that tent. Along those racks were 2 sets of rings, one colored orange, and the other blue. My mind floods through all my memories at the various carnivals set up back home in St.Petersburg. We lived in those Soviet era apartments with the old, creaky wood elevator. I remember always playing duck toss with my father, and how competitive I would get. I knew the rules, and I'd assume he did too. I smirk.


We both rush towards the tent, blocking out my surroundings to focus on that tent and that tent only. I feel like I can never run fast enough. Once arriving, I quickly drink some Almond Water. I knew what I had to do.


I accepted this challenge.

5 rings for me and the fiery gentleman. 5 attempts to score a ring on a duck. Thus, 5 attempts to win. All for free, of course. Good deal. I ignore all the beautiful colors around me and let my competitive nature take hold. A small bell positioned in the back lets out a ding. I take the initiative to start the first toss.

All or nothing.

I move my left arm forward with one of the orange rings in my hand, I aim for a duck in the center of the pool. I pull it back and toss. And I miss. 4 to go. 4 attempts to win. The Glowfolk next to me follows suit, and also misses. I notice a crowd forming around us, cheering. Making mini firework shows with their flames.


I vow to never disappoint them. I vow to give them the game they’re so eager to see

Let the games continue.

Each of those ducks represents a win, their small little heads so meticulously designed to fit each ring above it smugly. Yet also designed to make it difficult to have that ring land on itself. The way they spin represents how each child spins around in joy when they win a plushie. Each color represented an emotion one would feel at any given time in a game. Each duck tells a story. A paradox. One, when studied, gives interesting, intriguing, much-needed information. If failed to be processed properly, becomes meaningless. Meaningless to those who don't pay attention to its purpose, its lesson. And those same people will fall in the long run, and those who did will prosper.



What role does this play in the long run?

Take these rings. These rings are merely a tool. But its a tool needed to win. It's completely powerless unless it's used. It can only be used by those who wield that tool, know it's purpose, and exploits that purpose well. The ring's purpose is to be thrown on a duck. The effectiveness of these rings is 20% design, 80% user input. To win these games, you must know the purpose of the tools, if any, that are given to you.

And I knew exactly how to use these tools.

I repeat my movements from my first toss. I aim again for another duck that had moved itself into the center. A bright pink duck. My least favorite color. I pull back and throw. It slides off its left side and sinks into the water. 3 throws. 3 attempts. I watch the Glowfolk next to me make a calculated toss, and almost makes the throw, but slumps off the back of a yellow duck and sinks into the water. The inner layers of its body turn a reddish orange. The crowd behind me grows bigger, based on the spurge of rainbow colors reflecting off of the yellow tent. 

I throw my 3 & 4th ring in a similar manner, and the Glowfolk does the same. We are both down to our last ring.

1 shot. 1 opportunity. And I am going to take it, even I don't make it.

Let my childhood training against my dad prove me right. 

I feel the tension from each and every fiery being around soar. Goosebumps form. Sweat beads my forehead. My heart speeds up. 1 shot. 1 opportunity. 1 ring. 1 chance to win. I move my hand forward, pull back, and toss.


What can happen in a span of 6 seconds? Grab a pen? Stare at a map? Perhaps drink some water? It's really endless. But it was all spend staring at the million possible trajectories that last orange ring could go, with the tiniest of possible factors. Watching the ring feels like watching a slow-motion movie. Flying it's short-lived route to wherever it goes. I see it hit a duck on the left side of the pool.

It lands around the head.

It spins for what seems like forever.

Then, it stops.

The shot was made. 

Everything went quiet. 

Then the Glowfolk cheered, and my opponent shook hands with me.

== 3 Hours Later ==
I walk inside one of those multistory buildings, having savored the sweet taste of victory. Each of these buildings were hotels, some 3 to 10 stories high. The hallways were lined in linen cloth, with a super soft, puffy carpet. Every 20 feet or so was 2 hotel room doors back-to-back on both ends of the hallway. The doors themselves are made of a highly waxed mahogany wood. I go to the elevator in the back, and press the call button, the machinery room to the left lets out a loud hum. 20 seconds later, the elevator arrives. I walk into the elevator and go to the top floor. The doors shut right after I press the 5th floor button

It takes about 5 seconds for the elevator to start moving. The motor lets out a loud hum. A hydraulic. One of my favorite elevator types. About a minute, we arrive to the 5th floor, as the elevator slows down. My room is straight across from it. I hear the bell, then the doors open. I wall up to the door, and I unlock it. I set all my stuff down on one of the 2 beds in the room, and I flop down on the other one. The sheets feel like the most luxious of luxurious. They are of excellent quality. Pillows are not much different either.

I look back at all the fun I had. Being surrouned by all those Glowfolk. Cheering us on like they actually cared. They did actually care. You could see it in their eyes. I've never felt such support, confidence, stuff like that. You never really see a moment of solstice, nostalgia, or just sheer peacefulness like I felt here. This reminds me of my childhood. I could spend forever playing these carnival games. There's never too much Varity. You can never get bored here. There's always something new to do every day. And at least these GlowFolk play fair.


